rocky.teatime.database

Class DataSource

  • java.lang.Object
    • rocky.teatime.database.DataSource

  • public class DataSource
extends java.lang.Object
    Acts as an intermediary between the user/application and the underlying database. I acknolge that this does come at a small performance penalty but for a small database, this should not be too much of an issue.

        public Tea createEntry(java.lang.String teaName,
                       TeaType teaType,
                       int brewTime,
                       int brewSecond,
                       int minTemp,
                       int maxTemp,
                       java.lang.String picLocation,
                       float idealStrength,
                       boolean inStock)
        Adds a new item to the database?
        Parameters:
        teaName - The name of tea being added to the DB
        teaType - The type of tea (an enum, thus an int)
        brewTime - Brewtime of tea being added
        brewSecond - Brew time on second steeping
        minTemp - an integer
        maxTemp - an Integer, nothing surprising
        picLocation - Location of the tea's picture on the hard drive
        idealStrength - ideal strength to brew tea at, a float
        inStock - boolean communicating if the tea is in stock.
        Returns:
        A tea object corresponding with the new object

      • getEntry

        public Tea getEntry(long entryID)
             throws android.database.sqlite.SQLiteException
        Retuerns the Tea object from the database with an ID matching that of the supplied ID.
        Parameters:
        entryID - ID corresponding to the tea which we aim to search for
        Returns:
        Tea object from the database with an ID matching that of the supplied parameter
        Throws:
        android.database.sqlite.SQLiteException - if the no match to the query can be found. Unlikely to ever be thrown in practise.
